      //    It releases its contents to outside the cellThese organelles are shaped like sphere's, and contain enzymes that break down most kinds of biomoleculesThes organelles recycle larger molecules to be reusedThis organlles are similar to a digestive system, and digest proteins, acids, carbohydrates and dead or unwanted materialsGolgi BodyThe Golgi complex, also known as the Golgi apparatus or simply the Golgi, is a cytoplasmic organelle.The main function of the Golgi apparatus is to process and package macromolecules, such as proteins and lipids. They come to the Golgi after being built, and before they go to their destination.The Golgi complex inspects them for flaws and discards extra material added during their manufacture, wraps them up and then targets them for packaging. The Golgi releases special enzymes called lysosomes, which clean off any extra amino acids. When the package is ready, it is pinched off the Golgi and released into the cytoplasm.

       //   The golgi body is a sac-like body that packages proteins and carbohydrates into membrane-covered sacs for export from the cellThis organelle processes and packages macromoleculesThis organelle inspects macromolecules for flaws, before packaging them and sending them to their targetsThis organelle releases lysosomesMitochondrionThe mitochondria are the power houses of the cell. They make most of the cell's supply of adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a molecule that cells use as a source of energy. Their main job is this energy conversion. They oxidise glucose to provide energy for the cell. The process makes ATP, and is called cellular respiration.In addition to supplying cellular energy, mitochondria are involved in a range of other processes, such as signalling, cellular differentiation, cell death, as well as the control of the cell division cycle and cell growth.It is thought that mitochondria were once independent bacteria, and became part of the eukaryotic cells by being engulfed, a process called endosymbiosis.This organelle supplies the cell with energyThis organelle supplies the cell with a chemical called ATPThis organelle is thought to have once been a seperate bacteriaVacuolesVacuoles are organelles that are filled with fluid and remove waste products from the cellVacuoles are also digestive and help break down food material within the cell.It removes waste from the cellCentrosomeIn cell biology, the centrosome is an organelle that is the main place where cell microtubules are organized. They occur only in animal cells. Also, it regulates the cell division cycle, the stages which lead up to cell division.A centrosome is composed of two centrioles at right angles to each another. They are surrounded by a shapeless mass of protein.This organelle is the place where microtubles get organizedThis organelle is composed of two centroiles at right angles to each otherMicrotublesMicrotubules are found in biological cells as a part of the cytoskeleton. They are hollow tubes whose walls consist of 13 columns of tubulin molecules. Its main functions are to maintain a cell's shape, cell motility, chromosome movement in cell division, and organelle movement. They look like hollow noodles which transmit signals to our nervesThese are responsible for maintaining a cells shape, and chromosone movmentThese organelles are hollow tubes, and look like hollow noodlesNucleusThe nucleus is small and round, and it works as the cell's control center. It contains chromosomes which house the DNA. The human body contains billions of cells, most of which have a nucleus.  Inside the nucleus there are no membrane-bound sub-compartments. Its contents are not uniform, and a number of sub-nuclear bodies exist, made up of unique proteins, RNA molecules, and particular parts of the chromosomes.The nucleus is surrounded by a nuclear membrane. Large molecules cannot get through the double-layer nuclear membrane: it is impermeable to them. However, nuclear pores exist. They control the movement of molecules across the membrane. This contains the cells DNAThis organelle is small and round, and contains chromosones This organelle has a membrane, which larger molecules cannot crossRibosomesRibosomes are important cell organelles. A ribosome is a large complex of RNA and protein.It does RNA translation, building proteins from amino acids using messenger RNA as a template. Ribosomes are found in all living cells,The job of the ribosome is to make new proteins. It does this by moving along a strand of RNA and building a protein based on the code it reads. Making a protein this way is called translation. Ribosomes are usually found in the rough endoplasmic reticulum, but can also be found throughout the cytoplasm.This organelle is found in every cell, and is responsible for making protiensThis organelle is mainly found in the rough endoplasmic reticulum, but can be found in the cytoplasm as wellThis organelle translates RNA to create new protiensSmooth E