      Nuclear powerNuclear power is the controlled use of nuclear energy. Nuclear energy is energy in uranium that can be released by nuclear reactions in a machine called a nuclear reactor. This energy is made into electricity, which then can be used to power machines and heat homes.14% of the world's electricity came from nuclear power. Nuclear power plants also make radioactive waste that could be harmful if it is not stored properly. Nuclеar power plants produce less radioactive material than a coal fired power stationNuclear power plants opperate on a process known as fission, which takes a larger molecule and breaks it into smaller pieces, releasing energy in the processThe sun uses a process known as nuclear fussion, which joins two smaller molecules together to form a larger one, releasing a huge amount of heat. Researchers hope to use this form of energy in the future, as it is safer, more efficient, and greener that any current technologyIt generates energy from radioactive materialsThis power source operates on a process known as nuclear fissionThis power source has caused many disasters, such as Chernobyl, or Three Mile IslandHyrdo powerHydroelectricity is electricity that is made by the movement of water. It is usually made with dams that block a river to make a reservoir or collect water that is pumped there.When the water is "let go", the huge pressure behind the dam forces the water down pipes that lead to a turbine. This causes the turbine to turn, which turns a generator which makes electricity. The way the electricity is produced does not harm the environment as much as fossil fuels like oil or coal do. Hydroelectricity is very powerful and safe, and produces no waste.This form of power uses the flowing of water to generate electricityThis power source can cause flooding in some areas, and can damage the ecosystemOil powerOur main sources of energy today are fossil fuels. There are three main types of fossil fuels: coal, oil, and natural gas.Coal is a solid material that is burned to create heat in homes, or used in power plants to produce electricity. Oil is a liquid fossil fuel, used to produce gasoline. Natural gas can be used for cooking, heating, or generating electricity.All fossil fuels are nonrenewable resources. It took millions of years to form fossil fuels and we are currently using it up faster than it is being made.Another challenge to using nonrenewable energy sources is that they can cause pollution. Burning fossil fuels releases chemicals into the air and water.This is our main form of generating electricity currently, however it is harmful to the enviornmentThis power source uses organic material that is millions of years oldWind powerWind energy is the energy from the bulk movement of air. Wind is caused by pressure differences in the atmosphere which are caused by uneven heating of the earth by the sun. Air moves from areas of higher pressure to areas of lower pressure, which produces wind as a result. Wind power is the fastest growing renewable energy source. It is also the most widely available renewable energy source in the world. The height of a turbine tower can be over 100 meters, and the blades can be over 100 meters in diameter. A wind turbine this large can produce several megawatts of electricity, which is enough for a small townWind turbines are often found near oceans or plains, as the wind is stronger thereThis is the fastest growing renewable energy sourceThis energy source uses the movment of air to create electricityThis energy source can be over 100 meters tallThis energy source is often found near oceans, or fieldsSolar powerSolar energy is the energy that is in sunlight. Solar power plants convert sunlight into electricity, either directly using photovoltaics (PV), or indirectly using concentrated solar power (CSP).Concentrated solar power systems use lenses or mirrors and tracking systems to focus a large area of sunlight into a small beam. Photovoltaics converts light into electric current using the photoelectric effect.This form of energy uses the technology of photovoltaics, or concentrated solar power, to generate electricityThis form of energy can only produce electricity during the dayCalciteCalcite is a common rock forming mineralCalcite is found in all 3 types of rocksIt is used in all parts of our lives, from construction to pharmecutical industiresIt is a common rock building mineralSedimentary rockSedimentary rocks are formed in layers over time often at the bottom of lakes and oceans It is formed over time at the bottom of lakesIgneous rockThe rock shown here is Gnaisse which is a common form of igneous rockIgneous rocks are formed from volcanic activity, under high heat and pressureIt is formed from volcanic activityLimestoneLimestone is a sedimentary rockIt is often composed of the skeletal fragments of marine organisms such as coralIt is often made of skeletal fragments of marine organismsQuartzQuartz is a mineral made of silicon and oxygenIt is the second most abundant materialIt is made of silicon and oxygenMetamorphic rockA metamorphic rock is a type of rock which has been changed by extreme heat and pressure. Its name is from 'morph' (meaning form), and 'meta' (meaning change).The original rock may be sedimentary rock, igneous rock or another older metamorphic rock.for example marble is a metamorphic rock formed from limestone.This type of rock has been changed from extreme heat and pressure //ok, so here you need to have all the labels and information 
      FossilsIn this module you will learn about fossils, how they are formed, how they are found, and why they are importantA fossil is the remains or trace of an ancient living thing. Fossils of animals, plants or protists occur in sedimentary rock.In a typical fossil, the body form is retained, but the original molecules that made up the body have been replaced by some inorganic material, such as calcium carbonate (CaCO3) or silica (SiO2). It has been mineralised or petrified (literally, turned into rock).Some organisms fossilise well, others do not. The most common fossils are those left behind by organisms that produce hard materials.The study of fossils by geologists and biologists is known as paleontology. If the study puts living things in their ecological context it is called paleobiology.Types of fossilsMicroscopic or very tiny fossils are called "microfossils"; while larger, macroscopic fossils — such as those of seashells and mammals — are called "macrofossils".Although most fossils are formed from the hard parts of organisms, there are also indirect signs of prehistoric life. Examples such as a worm's trail or an animal's footprint are quite common. They are known as trace fossils.  Fossilized excrement, faeces or dung is known as a coprolite. Chemical traces of prehistoric organisms is called a chemofossil.Objects made by prehistoric people are called artifacts.CoelophysisCoelophysis is a small dinosaur that lived approximately 200 million years ago in the Late Triassic Period. It is named it Coelophysis—which means “hollow form”–because this dinosaur had hollow bones.This dinosaur was about 9 feet long, 3 feet high and weighed about 100 pounds at most. It’s hollow bone structure made it light and agile,This dinosaur lived about 200 million years ago, and had hollow bonesGiant ground slothGiant ground sloths were large, lumbering beasts that lived in the Americas during the Ice Age. They were directly related to today's modern sloths. They were also distantly related to anteaters and armadillos.By the end of the Great Ice Age, around 11,700 years ago, many believe that the giant ground sloths had become extinct. Some argue that they were around for many more thousands of years, though, surviving on islands in the Caribbean.This animal lived during the Ice Age, and are related to todays slothsMammothMammoths were hairy elephants of the genus Mammuthus. They lived in Europe until 4,500 years ago, and were adapted to cold climate. They were killed off by hunters and climate change.Like their modern relatives, mammoths were quite large. The largest known species reached heights in the region of 4 m (13.1 ft) at the shoulder and weights of up to 8 tonnes (8.8 short tons), while exceptionally large males may have exceeded 12 tonnes (13.2 short tons). Their diet was mainly grazing, these assumptions were based on mammoth feces and mammoth teeth, such as the molar shown hereEuropean mammoths had a major diet of C3 carbon fixation plants. This was determined by examining the isotopic data from the European mammoth teeth.Short faced bearThe short-faced bear or bulldog bear (Arctodus) is an extinct genus of bear endemic to North America during the Pleistocene era about 1.8 million years ago (mya) to 11,000 years ago. At that time it may have been one of the largest mammals that lived on land and ate meat.The short-faced bear lived in many parts of North America, ranging from Alaska to Mississippi. However, it lived mostly in southern areas, from northern Texas to New Jersey in the east; Aguascalientes, Mexico to the southwest; and with large concentrations in Florida.The short face bear found was estimated to be largest was 957 kg (2,110 lb). When it was standing on its hind (back) legs, the bear was 8–10 feet (2.4–3.0 m) tall.This animal lived during the Ice Age, and was the largest land carnivour at the timeSpinosaurusSpinosaurus (which means 'spiny lizard') was a huge semi-aquatic dinosaur from the Cretaceous, 112 to 97 million years ago. It had paddle-like feet and nostrils on top of its crocodile-like head.Estimates suggest that it was 12.6 to 18 metres (41 to 59 ft) in length and 7 to 20.9 tonnes (7.7 to 23.0 short tons) in weight. It lived in what is now Sahara Desert, but which then was mangrove forests alongside shoreline conditions, tidal flats and channels.Spinosaurus is known to have eaten fish. Evidence suggests that it lived both on land and in water like a modern crocodilian.This dinosaur is related to todays crocodileTrilobiteTrilobite (meaning "three lobed") are extinct arthropods. Their name is in reference to the three round parts, called lobes, across their headsTrilobites appeared some 600 million years ago during the Cambrian period. They belonged to the phylum Arthropoda (joint-footed), a phylum which to this day represents the most successful (78%) of all animal life forms, including crabs, centipedes, spiders, shrimps and insects. Trilobites are the earliest known animal to have vision. Some possessed eyes and some seem to have no eyes at all, while others had eyes made up of many parts that could see all around the animal. Trilobites ranged in length from 1 millimetre (0.04 in) to 72 centimetres (28 in), with a typical size range of 3–10 cm (1.2–3.9 in). These animals were one ofthe first to have eyes Greenhouse gasesIn this module you will learn about the common greenhouse gasses, and the effect they have on our atmosphere and climateThe Greenhouse effectGreenhouse gases reflect radiation that the Earth emits, and stop it from being lost into space. This causes the Earth's temperature to be higher than it would be without greenhouse gases. The name for this is the "greenhouse effect."This is the effect that causes radiation to be reflected back to EarthGreenhouse gassesMost greenhouse gases are natural - water vapor is the most common, and causes most of the greenhouse effect on Earth. Other greenhouse gases are carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, chlorofluorocarbon and ozone.Without greenhouse gases, the earth would be on average 33 degrees Celsius colder.These are gasses that cause the greenhouse effectWithout these gasses the earth would be 33 degrees colderWater vapourWater vapour is the most abundant greenhouse gas in the atmosphere, both by weight and by volume Water vapour will generally stay in the atmosphere for days (before precipitating out) while other greenhouse gases, such as carbon dioxide or methane, will stay in the atmosphere for a much longer period of time (ranging from years to centuries) thus contributing to warming for an extended period of time.Increased water vapor content in the atmosphere is referred to as a feedback process. Warmer air is able to hold more moisture. As the climate warms, air temperatures rise, more evaporation from water sources and land occurs, thus increasing the atmospheric moisture content. The water vapour feedback process is most likely responsible for a doubling of the greenhouse effect when compared to the addition of carbon dioxide on its own This is the most abundant greenhouse gasThis greenhous gas causes a feedback loop that doubles the greenhouse effectCarbon dioxideCarbon dioxide is a natually occuring gas, that is relased from decaying and living organisms, as well as volcanoesCarbon dioxide is also relased when burning fossil fuels such as coal or oil, and it is the most important contributer to man-made greenhouse gassesThis greenhouse gas is released by living and decaying organisms, as well as volcanoesThis greenhouse gas is the most important contributer of man-made greenhouse gassesMethaneMethane is a normal gas released from wetlands, growing rise, raising cattle, using natural gas, and mining coalHowever, methane traps alot of heat, and is concidered the second most important contributer to man-made greenhosue gassesThis greenhouse gas is realeased from wetlands, growing rice, and mining coalNitrous oxideNitrous oxide is a natural part of the nitrogen cycle, and is released from bacteria in the soil and oceanHowever, it is also released by some factories, power plants, and fertilizers. This gas damages the protective ozone layer, and is extreamly powerful This gas damages the protective ozone layer //not one
      EvaporationEnergy from the sun causes water to evaporate from bodies of waterThe main factors affecting evaporation are temperature, humidity, wind speed, and solar radiation.The principal source of water vapour is the oceans, but evaporation also occurs in soils, snow, and ice.Around 90 percent of the water vapor in the atmosphere got there through evaporation.Throught this process water rises to forms cloudsCondensationCondensation is the process of water vapour forming cloudsWater vapor gas condenses back into liquid water and ice, which you mainly see as clouds and then as rain and snow.Condensation happens because of temperature changes.This is the process during which water vapour forms cloudsPercipitationPrecipitation is when water falls from the atmosphere back to land.Depending on the temperature and weather this could be rain, snow, sleet, or even hail.This is how water returns from clouds to the ground levelTranspirationTranspiration is when plants release water on to their leaves that then evaporates into vapor.Around 10 percent of the water vapor in the atmosphere is estimated to come from transpiration.This is the process during which plants release water that is evaporatedMercuryMercury is the smallest, and closest planet to the sunIt completes one full revolution around the sun in 88 daysMercury has no atmosphereIt is the smallest planet in the solar systemVenusVenus has a thick atmosphere, of carbon dioxide and sulfuric acidThe average temprature on Venus is over 900 degreesVenus has over 100,000 active volcanosIt it has clouds made of acidEarthIt is the only known planet with lifeEarth's atmosphere is made up of about 80% nitrogen, and 20% oxygenThe surface of Earth is about 70% waterThe surface of this planet is 70% waterMarsThe average temprature on Mars is -63 degrees CelciusMars is about half the size of EarthMars is red because it is coverd in a layer of iron oxide - rustThis planet is covered in a layer of iron oxideJupiterJupiter is the largest planet in the solar systemJupiter is covered in clouds of hydrogen, helium and ammoniumJupiter has over 50 moons, some of which are as large as planetsIt is the largest planet in our solar systemSaturnSaturn is made of mostly hydrogen and heliumSaturn has rings made of dust and iceSaturn has over 52 moonsOne year on Saturn is over 10,759 Earth daysThis planet is famous for its ringsUranusUranus is the 7th planet from the sun, and the thrid gas giant, after Jupiter and SaturnUranus has been tipped on its side, most likely by another planetUranuus has 27 moons named after characters from William ShakespeareThis planet has been tipped on its sideNeptuneNeptune is the farthest planet from the sunNeptune has some of the fiersest storms in the solar system, with winds reaching over 1900 km/hThe average temprature on Neptune is -214 degrees CelsiusThis is the farthest planet from the sunPlutoPluto is a dwarf planetIt is mainly made of rock and iceIt is the nineth largest body orbiting the sunChemical reactionsIn this module you will learn about some common chemical reactions, what they are, and how they work
