        Salt and Silver NitrateSilver nitrate is a colorless crystalline solid. It dissolves in water, despite the fact that most silver compounds do not dissolve in water. It can also get dark if light shines on it, and is an oxidizing agent.The reaction between salt and silver nitrate produces silver chloride and sodium nitrate salt.Baking soda and Vinegar volcanoThis is the classic reaction that produces the baking soda and vinegar volcanoVinegar is a liquid used mostly in cooking. It can be made from wine or other liquids containing alcohol. Vinegar contains about 5% of Acetic acid. The acid makes it sour.\

          Baking soda is a white crystalline powder. It reacts with acids to produce carbon dioxide gas. It also reacts with bases to reduce their harmful effects.When sodium bicarbonate is heated, it releases carbon dioxide and water vapor (gas) and turns into sodium carbonate.When baking soda and vinegar react carbonic acid is produced. However, this acid is very unstable, and falls apart leaving only carbon dioxide and water.Bubbles begin floating around the top of the experiment. The bubbles, produced by this reaction, are actually the carbon dioxide escaping. WelcomeCreate your own Gold Ruberg machine to learn about the different types of energies, and how they can be transfered from one form to anotherYou can add objects from the menu on the left, when you are ready, click play!You can also choose from the prebuilt models, to get some ideas for your own machinesWant to put your machine to the test? Click the submit button to enter it into the weekly Gold Ruberg competition, and compete for prizes!Thermal energyMatter is made up of particles or molecules. These molecules move (or vibrate) constantly.A rise in the temperature of matter makes the particles vibrate faster. Thermal energy is what we call energy that comes from the temperature of matter. The hotter the substance, the more its molecules vibrate, and therefore the higher its thermal energy.However, thermal energy and temprature are not the same thing. The temperature of an object is to do with how hot or cold it is and is measured in degrees Celsius (°C). Meanwhile thermal energy depends on the number of molecules, and the temprature, it is meassure in Jolues To understand the differnece, consider the following example: A swimming pool at 40°C is at a lower temperature than a cup of tea at 90°C. However, the swimming pool contains a lot more water. Therefore, the pool has more thermal energy than the cup of tea even though the tea is hotter than the water in the pool.Kinetic energyAll moving things have kinetic energy. It is energy possessed by an object due to its motion or movement. These include very large things, like planets, and very small ones, like atoms. The heavier a thing is, and the faster it moves, the more kinetic energy it has.Mechanical energyMechanical energy is often confused with Kinetic and Potential Energy.Before that, we need to understand the word ‘Work’.‘Work’ is done when a force acts on an object to cause it to move, change shape, displace, or do something physical.For work to be done, the object must move, if you push as hard as you can on a wall, althought you exert a force, you do no work. However, if you move a pencil, althought the force used is smaller, you still do more work, because the pencil movedMechanical energy is the sum of kinetic and potential energy in an object that is used to do work. In other words, it is energy in an object due to its motion or position, or both.Gravitational energy Gravitational Potential energy is stored in the height of the object. Any time that a heavy object is kept high up, a force or power is likely to be holding it up there.Therefore, the higher the object, and the heavier it is, the more gravitational energy it hasElastic energyEach time energy is transferred into an object, two things happen. It is either used to do work, or it is stored in the object. If it is stored, the object is given potential energy that can be released to do work.Elastic energy is energy stored in stretched or compressed elastic materials.Elastic to kinetic energyElastic energy can be converted into kinetic energy. In this case the potential elastic energy stored in the spring is converted into kinetic energyIn this case, the total mechanical energy of the system remains the same, as no extra energy was created or destoryed, it only changed formsGravitational to kinetic energyGravitational potential energy can be converted into kinetic energy, or motion.As an object begins to fall, its gravitational energy decreases, but at the same time its kinetic energy increases. In this way, the total energy of the system remains the sameThermal to kinetic energyThermal energy can be transfered into kinetic energy. The thermal energy causes the molecules in the surrounding area to vibrate and move more, this in turn can push on other objects, causing kinetic energyAs the molecules push on some object, or on eachother, they begin to cool. In this way the thermal energy decreases, but the kinetic energy increases the same amountKinetic to elastic energyKinetic energy can be transffered into elastic potential energy. This can happen for exmaple when a ball falls on a spring, and compresses it. In this case, the kinetic energy of the ball is 0, as is the spring. However, the same amount of energy is still in the system, except it is now stored as potential energy in the springKinetic to gravitational energyKinetic energy can be transffered into gravitation energy. For example, when you throw a ball in the air as it rises it begins to slow, until eventually it stops and begins to fall againas the ball rises, its kinetic energy begins to become stored in gravitational potential energy. When the ball is at the top of its path, the kinetic energy is 0 (its not moving), this means that all the energy in the system is stored in gravitational potential energyKinetic to thermal energyKinetic energy can be transffered into thermal energy.WavesIn this module you will learn about basic wave terminologyThere are lots of waves all around us in everyday life. Sound is a type of wave that moves through matter and then vibrates our eardrums so we can hear. Light is a special kind of wave that is made up of photons. You can drop a rock into a pond and see waves form in the water. We even use waves (microwaves) to cook our food Waves can be divided into various categories depending on their characteristics. All waves can be categorized as either mechanical or electromagnetic.Mechanical wavesMechanical waves are waves that require a medium. This means that they have to have some sort of matter to travel through. These waves travel when molecules in the medium collide with each other passing on energy.One example of a mechanical wave is sound. Sound can travel through air, water, or solids, but it can't travel through a vacuum. It needs the medium to help it travel. Other examples include water waves, seismic waves, and waves traveling through a spring.This type of wave requries a mediumSound waves are an exmaple of this type of waveThis type of wave cannot travel throught a vacuumWater waves is this type of waveElectromagnetic wavesElectromagnetic waves are waves that can travel through a vacuum (empty space). They don't need a medium or matter.They travel through electrical and magnetic fields that are generated by charged particles. Examples of electromagnetic waves include light, microwaves, radio waves, and X-rays.This type of wave doesn't require a mediumMicrowaves are this type of waveRadio waves are this type of waveLight is this kind of waveTravelling wavesAnother way to describe a wave is by the direction that its disturbance is traveling. We can categorize waves into two categories, transverse and longitudinal wavesTransverse wavesTransverse waves are waves where the disturbance moves perpendicular to the direction of the wave.You can think of the wave moving left to right, while the disturbance moves up and down. One example of a transverse wave is a water wave where the water moves up and down as the wave passes through the ocean.This type of wave causes disturbances perpendicular to the direction of the waveWater waves move in this type of wayLongitudinal wavesLongitudinal waves are waves where the disturbance moves in the same direction as the wave.One example of this is a wave moving through a stretched out slinky or spring. If you compress one portion of the slinky and let go, the wave will move left to right. At the same time, the disturbance (which is the coils of the springs moving), will also move left to right. Another classic example of a longitudinal wave is sound. As sound waves propagate through a medium, the molecules collide with each other in the same direction as the sound is moving.Sound waves move in this type of wayThis type of wave causes a disturbance in the same direction as the wave
          //6
          AmplitudeThe amplitude of a wave is a measure of the displacement of the wave from its rest position, in other words it is how high/low the wave goesIn the case of water waves this can be thought of as the height of the wave, the higher the wave the larger the amplitudeThe amplitude is a measure of the strength or intensity of the wave. For example, when looking at a sound wave, the amplitude will measure the loudness of the sound. The energy of the wave also varies in direct proportion to the amplitude of the wave.This is the measure of the displacement of the waveThis can be thought of as the height of the waveThis is a measure of the strength or intensity of the waveThis represents the loudness for sound waves
          //7
          WavelengthThe wavelength of a wave is the distance between two corresponding points on back-to-back cycles of a wave.This can be measured between two crests of a wave or two troughs of a wave. The wavelength is usually represented in physics by the Greek letter lambda (λ).In the term of water waves this can be thought of as how "long" the waves areThis measures the distance between two corresponding points on back to back cycles of a wave
          //8
          Frequency and PeriodThe frequency of a wave is the number of times per second that the wave cycles. Frequency is measured in Hertz or cycles per second. The frequency is often represented by the lower case "f."The period of the wave is the time between wave crests. The period is measured in time units such as seconds. The period is usually represented by the upper case "T."The period and frequency are closely related to each other. The period equals 1 over the frequency and the frequency is equal to one over the period. They are reciprocals of each other
          //9
          Velocity of a WaveAnother important property of a wave is the speed of propagation. This is how fast the disturbance of the wave is moving. The speed of mechanical waves depends on the medium that the wave is traveling through. For example, sound will travel at a different speed in water than in air.velocity = frequency * wavelength or v = f * λ
