        BiochemistryIn this module you will learn about the basics of carbohydrates, lipids, protiens, and nucleic acid, as well as celular respirationNucleic AcidsNucleic acids are large molecules where genetic information is stored. There are two types of nucleic acids: deoxyribonucleic acid, better known as DNA and ribonucleic acid, better known as RNA.Nucleic acids allow organisms to transfer genetic information from one generation to the next. When a cell divides, its DNA is copied and passed from one cell generation to the next generation.DNA is organized into chromosomes and found within the nucleus of our cells. Its function in any cell is to carry the sequence of bases which will be transcribed into RNA. RNA then has many function within the cellThese molecules are responsible for passing on genetic informationThese molecules are used to create another important molecule known as RNAThese molecules are organized into chromosonesCarbohydrateCarbohydrates are chemical compounds that contain only oxygen, hydrogen and carbon. They are made up of joined-up sugars. Sugars have the general formula Cm(H2O)n, and are also known as saccharides.Certain carbohydrates are an important storage and transport form of energy in most organisms, including plants and animals.Carbohydrates are very good for energy, but, if a person eats more than needed, the extra is changed into fat.These molecules are very good for energy, however if too much of them are eaten, they are changed into fatThese molecules are made of joined-up sugarsCellular respirationCellular respiration is what cells do to break up sugars into a form that the cell can use as energy. Cellular respiration takes in food and uses it to create ATP, a chemical which the cell uses for energy. Usually, this process uses oxygen, and is called aerobic respiration.It also produces carbon dioxide as a waste product, which then enters the circulatory system. The carbon dioxide is taken to the lungs, where it is exchanged for oxygen. When they don't get enough oxygen, the cells use anaerobic respiration, which doesn’t require oxygen. However, this process produces lactic acid, and is not as efficient as when oxygen is used. The equation for this process is Glucose (sugar) + Oxygen → Carbon dioxide + Water + Energy (as ATP)Every cell does this to produce energyProtiensProteins are long-chain molecules built from small units known as amino acids. They are joined together with peptide bonds.Proteins are essential to all cells. proteins take part in virtually every process in cellsProteins do different things depending on their shape. They can be found in meat or muscle. They are used for growth and repair, making tissue cells and used for strengthening the bones.There are four things that determine what a protein will do. The first is the order of the amino acids. he second is the little twists in the chain. The third is how the entire thing is folded up. The fourth is whether it is made up of different sub-unitsThese molecules are made up of small units known as amino acidsThese molecules are found in large numbers in meat and muscleThese molecules are used for growth, repair, making tissue cells and strengthening bones amoung othersLipidsA lipid is a type of organic molecule found in living things. It is oily or waxy. Fats are made from lipid molecules.Sources of lipid can be found in algae, seeds, meat, cheese, butter and fish. Lipids are long chains of carbon and hydrogen molecules. Lipids are classified as simple and complex. Examples of complex molecules could be steroids or phospholipids.A very important biological function of lipids is as lipid bilayers, the basis of many cell membranes. Another function of lipids is to serve as an energy reserve.In summary, lipids are a group of naturally occurring molecules that include fats, waxes, sterols, fat-soluble vitamins (such as vitamins A, D, E, and K), glycerides, phospholipids, and others. The main biological functions of lipids include storing energy, signalling, and acting as components of cell membranes.These molecules naturally occure in fats, waxes and fat-soluble vitaminsThese molecules are classified as either simple or complexThe main functions of this molelcule include signalling, storing energy, and building the cell membraneHeartThe Heart's function is to pump blood throughout the bodyThe Heart is considered a muscleThe heart consists of four different chambers: the left atrium, the right atrium, the left ventricle and the right ventricle.This organ is made up of four different chambersBrainThe Brain allows us to think, store memories, analyze and make judgments while at the same time controlling other areas automatically, such as breathing.The human brain weighs 3 pounds and is made up of 60% fat. The brain consists of the cerebrum, the brainstem, and the cerebellum.The cerebrum: this is responsible for a number of things like speech, motion, it also controls movement and learning it’s the largest part of the brain.The cerebellum: its main function is for helping with muscle movements, posture and balance\
          The brainstem: plays a really important function by connecting the cerebrum and cerebellum to your spinal cord. It automatically looks after many of our bodies function like body temperature, digestion, heart rate and even things like sneezing and coughing.This organ controls all of our bodys vital functionsLungsBlood runs through our body, goes to the lungs to pick up oxygen from the air we breathe in and then drops off carbon dioxide, which we breathe out.The average adult individual breathes almost 11,000 liters of air every single day.The lungs have special little hairs in tubes in your lungs that move up and out. This helps the special cells that produce mucus. Mucus in the lungs is also specialized as it catches bacteria, dirt and dust that you breathe in as well as bacteria in the air.This organ supplies blood with oxygen, and removes carbon dioxideLiverThe liver is involved in almost every vital function of the body, such as making and storing energy; producing proteins vital for body function; processing drugs, and playing a vital role in immune function. Your liver is the second largest organ (after the skin), it weights about 3 poundsIt's the only organ that can completly regenerate, it only needs 25% of the orignial tissue, and can regrow in less than two weeksIt is the second largest organ in the bodyKidneyKidneys are two bean shaped organs, that are responsible for creating urineKidneys make hormones. The two most important ones that it makes are erythropoetin and renin.The kidney's most important work is keeping homeostasis. Homeostasis means that the body keeps a stable environment inside itselfThis organ is important in keeping homeostasisCarbon DioxideCarbon dioxide is a gas that is present in the air.Plants collect carbon dioxide through tiny holes called stomates.Carbon dioxide is then combined with water and oxygen in a process known as photosynthesisThis gas is needed to complete photosynthesisEnergy from the SunSunlight is absorbed by a green chemical in the leaves, called chlorophilThe energy from the sun is used to split the water molecules into hydrogen and oxygenThis source of energy is required for photosynthesisOxygenDuring the process of photosynthesis, stomates are used to expel a gas called oxygen.Oxygen is very important for animals like humans – we need it to breathe!This is biproduct of photosynthesis is expelled by the plantGlucoseGlucose is a type of sugar, that the plant uses as energy to grow, and reproduceGlucose is produced throught photosynthesis, the word equation would be: Carbon Dioxide + Water + Light Energy = Glucose + OxygenThis is what the plant produces throught photosynthesis, which it uses to grow and reproduceEcological interactionIn this module you will learn about the different interactions in a food web and food chainFood chainEvery living plant and animal must have energy to survive. Plants rely on the soil, water, and the sun for energy. Animals rely on plants as well as other animals for energy.In an ecosystem, plants and animals all rely on each other to live. Scientists sometimes describe this dependence using a food chain or a food web.A food chain describes how different organisms eat each other, starting out with a plant and ending with an animal. Food WebIn any ecosystem there are many food chains and, generally, most plants and animals are part of several chains. When you draw all the chains together you end up with a food web.This describes an ecosystem with many food chainsTrophic LevelsSometimes scientists describe each level in a food web with a trophic level. Here are the five trophic levels:   Level 1: Plants (producers)Level 2: Animals that eat plants or herbivores (primary consumers)Level 3: Animals that eat herbivores (secondary consumers, carnivores)Level 4: Animals that eat carnivores (tertiary consumers, carnivores)Level 5: Animals at the top of the food chain are called apex predators. Nothing eats these animals.These levels describe each level in a food web
          //kelp and plankton
          Producers Plants are producers. This is because they produce energy for the ecosystem.They do this because they absorb energy from sunlight through photosynthesis. They also need water and nutrients from the soil, but plants are the only place where new energy is made.Primary Consumers //crab
          Animals are consumers. This is because they don't produce energy, they just use it up. Animals that eat plants are called primary consumers or herbivores.These animals eat plantsAnother name for these animals is herbivores
          // squid, krill
          Secondary ConsumersAnimals that eat other animals are called secondary consumers or carnivores.These animals eat herbivores.Another name for these consumers is carnivores
          //penguin, walrus, seal, seagull
          Tertiary Consumer If a carnivore eats another carnivore, it is called a tertiary consumer.These are animals that eat other carnivoresOmnivore //fish
          Some animals play both roles, eating both plants and animals. They are called omnivores.These animals eat both plants and animalsDecomposers //plankton
          Decomposers eat decaying matter (like dead plants and animals). They help put nutrients back into the soil for plants to eat. Examples of decomposers are worms, bacteria, and fungi.These animals eat decaying matterWorms, bacteria and fungi belong to this group
          //killer whale, whale
          Apex preditorApex predators are predators with no natural predators of their own. They are at the top of their food chain.These animals are at the top of their food chainThese animals have not preditors  of their ownPlate TectonicsIn this module you will learn about plate tectonics, their different types, and how they shape our worldDivergent boundariesIn some places, the plates are pulling apart. New crust is pushed up from below.  These are called divergent boundaries and they create rifts or valleys.Large lakes sometimes form in rifts.These places create rifts or valleysConvergent boundariesIn other places the plates are pushing against each other, creating mountains Sometimes one crust is dragged beneath – or subducted – below another oneOcean plates are heavier than continental plates so these plates are always dragged beneath.These boundaries create mountainsTransform boundariesA transform boundary happens when plates slide past each other but neither collide nor rip apart.The San Andreas Fault in California is a transform boundary.At these boundaries, plates slide past each other10020

